text: First of all, this is not a copy of Harry Potter, if anything Rowling got Harry Potter ideas from this book series which was written in the 1970s.  I've read the book the movie gets it's name from, and it looks like the movie changed it quite a bit.  Cate Blanchett's character, Mrs. Zimmerman, is supposed to be old and very wrinkled.  The boy character, Lewis, is supposed to be overweight, shy, awkward, and not athletic at all.  There is no tentacle monster living in the closet, no attacking pumpkins, and no creepy puppet people(although that is pretty freaky and cool).  Lewis never begs to be taught magic, but is allowed to read certain books, but not others.  There is an ominous clock that can be heard ticking. Uncle Jonathan and Mrs. Zimmerman do wondrous and frightening magic.  There is evil lurking to destroy them, and perhaps the world???  Lewis' adventures take place in the late 1940's, so there would be no black kids in his school.  If they wanted to change things, maybe change the time setting of the movie and make it take place in the modern era??  That way Lewis' friend, Rose Rita, could legitimately be of any race, which would be unlikely in 1948.  Maybe it is picky, but Hollywood has to change things for no good reason.  I think they did good job overall with the feel of the book.  Hopefully it will still be close enough to be good.  I highly recommend read the John Bellairs series, even as adults they are fun!

text: I really hate to say this because I'm a big fan of the acting talents of all the people present, and I don't know enough about the source material to be hyped up by concept of this being made alone, but this movie appears to fail by way of the very message it intends to give:   "I can give you the right books, teach you the right spells, but that last 1%, that's up to you."  That last 1% is the magic part, see?  The actual visual effects are such shit that you are completely taken out of the movie.   The overall humorous tone to the magical world at times has the potential to be charming, and I see Jack Black and Cate Blanchett conveying this as perfectly as they possibly could have....while reacting to a green screen (possibly within a green screen room) to what appears to the audience as a much too obviously cartoon, overly animated LSD apparition. I had to check myself.  Visual effects don't count for everything but it's is a talent that is very difficult to teach. As a person who has only dabbled in effects in the smallest possible of ways; rotoscoping or key framing animation for hours with little to show for it, I can say this is a very technical and precision-based task that being proficient at technically will not give you that last bit of talent or intuition that can ever be taught. Making a movie, too, is this way, and we can see how efforts have changed over the years to favor a less messy, less risky world of visual effects that is just shy of being a completely robotic process that lacks that element of real life earthy chaos.   So went the ways of Ninja Turtles, so went the ways of Ghostbusters, both of which were disappointing for different reasons, but no one could quite say why.  With the above statement in mind, as well as my first, I will say that my favorite thing about this trailer is the acting talents of those seen, and that this isn't something I immediately knew the course of. Meaning it is probably pretty old. Good.

text: This is a fun movie and a great family film. Jack Black is great like always and to see him play a warlock is a treat. Cate Blanchet is great as well her and Jack Black has good chemistry and the banter between the two is funny. Owen Vaccaro who plays Lewis the kid was great as well. I love how they gave some of the objects in the house and the house its self a personality. The villain in the movie Issac Izard was well portrayed by Kyle McLachlan and he was a decent bad guy. The special effects were great and this movie felt like a good movie for the Halloween season. I would like to see more of Jack Black and Cate Blanchett working together in the future. All in all, this is a fun and enjoyable movie. There is this one scene where you go what that is weird and looks strange but I won't go into that. The acting is great, the story is great, special effects are great and the directing is great. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is Cinematastic rating 5/5
